]}, "url": {}}, "fastFollowersCount": 0, "favouritesCount": 10120, "hasCustomTimelines": true, "isTranslator": false, "mediaCount": 920, "statusesCount": 8783, "withheldInCountries": [], "affiliatesHighlightedLabel": {}, "possiblySensitive": false, "pinnedTweetIds": ["2051317776820662338"], "profile_bio": {"description": "Proudly Yoruba. Fan of Davido\u2764\ufe0f\u200d\ud83d\udd25 Heavy on BURNA\ud83d\udd25\ud83e\udd8d\nODG vibes \ud83e\udd81 30BG energy \u26a1Tweets you\u2019ll relate to daily \ud83e\udd1d\nCome for the vibes, stay for the energy \u26a1", "entities": {"description": {}}}, "isAutomated": false, "automatedBy": null}, "extendedEntities": {}, "card": null, "place": {}, "entities": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": [{"id_str": "1450961903694622723", "indices": [0, 13], "name": "Baddy of Lagos \ud83d\udc51", "screen_name": "_belikebaddy"}]}, "quoted_tweet": null, "retweeted_tweet": null, "isLimitedReply": false, "communityInfo": null, "article": null}, {"type": "tweet", "id": "2051642505280778290", "url": "https://x.com/Plantmore1/status/2051642505280778290", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/Plantmore1/status/2051642505280778290", "text": "About 7 years ago John Deere brought out their tractor engineers to ask me about my likes and dislikes of the first RX tractors. There were many of both. I asked for a small window that opened, they listened and we recently upgraded and are enjoying the fresh air! https://t.co/8dcHhPz8d1", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 1, "replyCount": 1, "likeCount": 26, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount": 1168, "createdAt": "Tue May 05 12:37:45 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 0, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2051642505280778290", "displayTextRange": [0, 264], "inReplyToUserId": null, "inReplyToUsername": null, "author": {"type": "user", "userName": "Plantmore1", "url": "https://x.com/Plantmore1", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/Plantmore1", "id": "55572638", "name": "Brent", "isVerified": false, "isBlueVerified": false, "verifiedType": null, "profilePicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1439078166010679296/69bHed35_normal.jpg", "coverPicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_banners/55572638/1526214915", "description": "", "location": "Rm 1x3", "followers": 4759, "following": 1054, "status": "", "canDm": true, "canMediaTag": true, "createdAt": "Fri Jul 10 14:17:34 +0000 2009", "entities": {"description": {"urls": []}, "url": {}}, "fastFollowersCount": 0, "favouritesCount": 31114, "hasCustomTimelines": true, "isTranslator": false, "mediaCount": 668, "statusesCount": 24922, "withheldInCountries": [], "affiliatesHighlightedLabel": {}, "possiblySensitive": false, "pinnedTweetIds": [], "profile_bio": {"description": "", "entities": {"description": {}}}, "isAutomated": false, "automatedBy": null}, "extendedEntities": {"media": [{"display_url": "pic.twitter.com/8dcHhPz8d1", "expanded_url": "https://twitter.com/Plantmore1/status/2051642505280778290/photo/1", "ext_media_availability": {"status": "Available"}, "features": {"large": {"faces": [{"h": 136, "w": 136, "x": 1238, "y": 744}]}, "orig": {"faces": [{"h": 136, "w": 136, "x": 1238, "y": 744}]}}, "id_str": "2051642472908914691", "indices": [265, 288], "media_key": "3_2051642472908914691", "media_results": {"id": "QXBpTWVkaWFSZXN1bHRzOgwAAQoAARx45fWD1wADCgACHHjl/Q1acDIAAA==", "result": {"__typename": "ApiMedia", "id": "QXBpTWVkaWE6DAABCgABHHjl9YPXAAMKAAIceOX9DVpwMgAA", "media_key": "3_2051642472908914691"}}, "media_url_https": "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HHjl9YPXAAMMKrn.jpg", "original_info": {"focus_rects": [{"h": 860, "w": 1536, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 1536, "w": 1536, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 1751, "w": 1536, "x": 0, "y": 0}, {"h": 2048, "w": 1024, "x": 51, "y": 0}, {"h": 2048, "w": 1536, "x": 0, "y": 0}], "height": 2048, "width": 1536}, "sizes": {"large": {"h": 2048, "w": 1536}}, "type": "photo", "url": "https://t.co/8dcHhPz8d1"}]}, "card": null, "place": {}, "entities": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "quoted_tweet": null, "retweeted_tweet": null, "isLimitedReply": false, "communityInfo": null, "article": null}, {"type": "tweet", "id": "2051708691938787367", "url": "https://x.com/dirtcheapbanks/status/2051708691938787367", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/dirtcheapbanks/status/2051708691938787367", "text": "I learned patience from my father who never owned a stock in his life but spent forty-seven years selling John Deere tractors to farmers who paid in October for equipment they ordered in March, and he would sit in his office with the fake wood paneling and the calendar from the parts distributor and wait for harvest checks to clear while younger salesmen chased financing deals and manufacturer incentives, and every October the farmers came back with cash because they knew my father would be there, same desk, same handwriting on the same carbon-copy order forms that corporate kept threatening to replace with computers.\n\nBanks are farming with money instead of corn, and the patience works the same way, except instead of waiting for harvest you wait for loan growth and net interest margin expansion and the slow compound of retained earnings building book value quarter by quarter while analysts chase growth stocks and bitcoin and whatever Jim Cramer screamed about on television last night, and you sit there watching a bank in rural Mississippi trade for sixty-two cents on the dollar because their efficiency ratio hit seventy-eight percent and their loan-to-deposit ratio dropped to eighty-one percent and the market decided that means they are dying.\n\nThe market is not patient. The market wants earnings to grow fifteen percent annually and wants loan books to expand and wants branches to look like Apple Stores, and when a bank president says he's being conservative with credit and taking provisions for agricultural loans that might go bad in eighteen months, the market sells the stock down to fifty-eight cents on the dollar and moves on to find banks that will promise growth and margin expansion and digital transformation initiatives that sound good in quarterly conference calls.\n\nPatient is rarer than smart, and patient compounds at rates that smart cannot match, because smart tries to time interest rate cycles and predict merger activity and model out efficiency improvements, while patient just sits there collecting dividends that get raised every December and watching book value grow at eight percent annually while the stock price follows earnings with the lag of a freight train, slow to fall and slower to rise but always eventually arriving where the math says it should.\n\nI have owned the same bank stock for eleven years and in that time the shares have been acquired twice by larger banks and spun back out once when the acquiring bank decided community banking was not strategic, and through all of that the dividend kept getting paid and the book value kept growing and the loans kept performing, and when I got the tender offer notices I just rolled the proceeds into another bank trading below tangible book because I had learned that owning banks is not about picking the right bank, it is about having the patience to own any reasonable bank long enough for mean reversion to work.\n\nThe farmers my father sold to understood this. They bought land in 1976 when corn was expensive and in 1982 when corn was cheap, and they farmed the same acres through drought and flood and farm crisis and grain embargos, and they retired with more money than the doctors and lawyers in town because they had the patience to own dirt while everyone else chased returns, and their sons farm the same land now with GPS and satellite imagery and yield monitors, but the patience part has not changed.\n\nBanks are the same dirt, just different crops. The branches may look tired and the loan officers may drive trucks with two hundred thousand miles and the board meetings may happen in conference rooms with carpet from the Carter administration, but underneath all that is the simple math of taking deposits and making loans and keeping the spread, and that math has worked through every interest rate cycle and technology disruption and regulatory change since Alexander Hamilton, and it will keep working as long as people need money and have money, which is to say forever.\n\nI do not recommend this patience. I am describing it. When you sit in a folding chair at annual shareholder meetings where twelve people show up and the CEO knows everyone's first name and the coffee tastes like it was made in 1987, you become a person who measures time differently, who thinks in decades instead of quarters, who understands that the best returns come from the most boring businesses run by the most careful people in the smallest towns where nothing ever happens except the slow accumulation of wealth that no one talks about because talking about it would ruin it.", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 0, "replyCount": 1, "likeCount": 14, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount": 856, "createdAt": "Tue May 05 17:00:45 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 5, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2051708691938787367", "displayTextRange": [0, 278], "inReplyToUserId": null, "inReplyToUsername": null, "author": {"type": "user", "userName": "dirtcheapbanks", "url": "https://x.com/dirtcheapbanks", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/dirtcheapbanks", "id": "2016890608271458304", "name": "Dirt Cheap Banks", "isVerified": false, "isBlueVerified": true, "verifiedType": null, "profilePicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/2016891147218505729/nG0X3r3A_normal.jpg", "coverPicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_banners/2016890608271458304/1769699397", "description": "", "location": "Federal Reserve", "followers": 64807, "following": 28, "status": "", "canDm": true, "canMediaTag": true, "creat